{2.2 Mathematical description of internal forces in solids}

{Our next objective is to outline the mathematical formulas that describe internal and external forces acting on a solid.

Just as there are many different strain measures, there are several different definitions of internal force.

We shall see that internal forces can be described as a second order tensor, which must be symmetric.

Thus, internal forces can always be quantified by a set of six numbers, and the various different definitions are all equivalent.}

{ }

{ }

![](media/2.2-Internal forces_files/image004.gif){} \\

\subparagraph{\texorpdfstring{2.2.1 Surface traction and internal body force}{2.2.1 Surface traction and internal body force}}

{ }

{Forces can be applied to a solid body in two ways.  }

{ }

{(i) A force can be applied to its boundary: examples include fluid pressure, wind loading, or forces arising from contact with another solid.  }

{ }

{(ii) The solid can be subjected to body forces, which act on the interior of the solid.

Examples include gravitational loading, or electromagnetic forces.}

![](media/2.2-Internal forces_files/image006.gif){} \\

{ }

{ }

{![](media/2.2-Internal forces_files/image008.jpg) }{The \emph{surface traction vector} t at a point on the surface represents the force acting on the surface per unit area of the deformed solid.  }

{ }

{Formally, let dA be an element of area on a surface.

Suppose that dA is subjected to a force $$

d\mathbf{P}$$

.  Then}

$$

\mathbf{t} = \lim\limits_{dA\rightarrow 0}\frac{d\mathbf{P}}{dA}$$

{The resultant force acting on any portion S of the surface of the deformed solid is}

$$

\mathbf{P} = {\int\limits_{S}{\mathbf{t}\, dA}}$$

{Surface traction, like `true stress,' should be thought of as acting on the deformed solid.}

![](media/2.2-Internal forces_files/image010.gif){} \\

{ }

{ }

{![](media/2.2-Internal forces_files/image008.jpg) Normal and shear tractions}

{ }

{The traction vector is often resolved into components acting normal and tangential to a surface, as shown in the picture.  }

{ }

{The normal component is referred to as the normal traction, and the tangential component is known as the shear traction.}

{ }

{Formally, let n}{ denote a unit vector normal to the surface.

Then}

$$

\mathbf{t}_{\mathbf{n}} = \left( {\mathbf{t} \cdot \mathbf{n}} \right)\mathbf{n}\,\,\,\,\,\,\,\,\,\,\,\,\,\,\,\,\mathbf{t}_{\mathbf{t}} = \mathbf{t} - \mathbf{t}_{\mathbf{n}}$$

{ }

![](media/2.2-Internal forces_files/image012.gif){} \\

{ }

{![](media/2.2-Internal forces_files/image008.jpg) }{The \emph{body force vector} denotes the external force acting on the interior of a solid, per unit mass.}

{ }

{Formally, let dV denote an infinitesimal volume element within the deformed solid, and let $$

\rho$$

denote the mass density (mass per unit deformed volume).

Suppose that the element is subjected to a force }$$

d\mathbf{P}$$

.{  }Then

$$

\mathbf{b} = \frac{1}{\rho}\lim\limits_{dV\rightarrow 0}\frac{d\mathbf{P}}{dV}$$

{The resultant body force acting on any volume V  within the deformed solid is}

$$

\mathbf{P} = {\int\limits_{V}{\rho\,\mathbf{b}\, dV}}$$

{ }

{ }

![](media/2.2-Internal forces_files/image014.gif){} \\

\paragraph{\texorpdfstring{2.2.2 Traction acting on planes within a solid}{2.2.2 Traction acting on planes within a solid}}

{ }

{Every plane in the interior of a solid is subjected to a distribution of traction.

To see this, consider a loaded, solid, body in static equilibrium.

Imagine cutting the solid in two.

The two parts of the solid must each be in static equilibrium.

This is possible only if forces act on the planes that were created by the cut.}

{ }

{ }

{ }

{ }

{![](media/2.2-Internal forces_files/image015.jpg) The internal traction vector T(n) represents the force per unit area acting on a section of the deformed body across a plane with outer normal vector n.}{}

![](media/2.2-Internal forces_files/image017.gif){} \\

{ }

{Formally, let dA be an element of area in the interior of the solid, with normal n.

Suppose that the material on the underside of dA is subjected to a force $$

d\mathbf{P}^{(\mathbf{n})}$$

across the plane dA.

Then}

$$

\mathbf{T}(\mathbf{n}) = \lim\limits_{dA\rightarrow 0}\frac{d\mathbf{P}^{(\mathbf{n})}}{dA}$$

{Note that internal traction is the force per unit area of the deformed solid, like `true stress'}

{ }

{ }

{ }

{ }

{ }

![](media/2.2-Internal forces_files/image019.gif){} \\

{![](media/2.2-Internal forces_files/image008.jpg) }{The resultant force acting on any internal volume \emph{V with boundary surface A within a deformed solid is}}

$$

\mathbf{P} = {\int\limits_{A}{\mathbf{T}(\mathbf{n})dA +}}{\int\limits_{V}{\rho\,\mathbf{b}\, dV}}$$

{The first term is the resultant force acting on the internal surface A, the second term is the resultant body force acting on the interior V.}

{ }

{ }

{ }

{ }

{ }

{ }

{![](media/2.2-Internal forces_files/image008.jpg) Newton's third law (every action has an equal and opposite reaction) requires that}

![](media/2.2-Internal forces_files/image021.gif){} \\

$$

\mathbf{T}( - \mathbf{n}) = - \mathbf{T}(\mathbf{n})$$

{}

{To see this, note that the forces acting on planes separating two adjacent volume elements in a solid must be equal and opposite.}

{ }

{ }

{ }

\frac{dA_{1}}{dA^{(n)}} = n_{1}\,\,\,\,\,\,\,\,\,\,\frac{dA_{2}}{dA^{(n)}} = n_{2}\,\,\,\,\,\,\,\,\,\frac{dA_{3}}{dA^{(n)}} = n_{3}\,\,\,\,\,\,\,\,\,\lim\limits_{dA^{(n)}\rightarrow 0}\frac{dV}{dA^{(n)}} = 0$$

{so}

$$

\mathbf{T}(\mathbf{n}) = \mathbf{T}(\mathbf{e}_{1})n_{1} - \mathbf{T}(\mathbf{e}_{2})n_{2} - \mathbf{T}(\mathbf{e}_{3})n_{3}$$

{or, using index notation}

$$

T_{i}(\mathbf{n}) = T_{i}(\mathbf{e}_{1})n_{1} + T_{i}(\mathbf{e}_{2})n_{2} + T_{i}(\mathbf{e}_{3})n_{3}$$

{}

{The significance of this result is that the tractions acting on planes with normals in the $$

\mathbf{e}_{1}$$

, $$

\mathbf{e}_{2}$$

, and $$

\mathbf{e}_{3}$$

directions completely characterize the internal forces that act at a point.

Given these tractions, we can deduce the tractions acting on any other plane.

This leads directly to the definition of the Cauchy stress tensor in the next section.}

{ }

{ }

\paragraph{\texorpdfstring{2.2.3 The Cauchy (true) stress tensor}{2.2.3 The Cauchy (true) stress tensor}}

{ }

{Consider a solid which deforms under external loading.

Let $$

\left\{ {\mathbf{e}_{1},\mathbf{e}_{2},\mathbf{e}_{3}} \right\}$$

\begin{matrix} {\sigma_{ij} = T_{j}(\mathbf{e}_{i})} \\ {\equiv \left\{ \begin{array}{l} {\sigma_{11} = T_{1}(\mathbf{e}_{1})\,\,\,\,\,\,\,\,\,\,\,\sigma_{12} = T_{2}(\mathbf{e}_{1})\,\,\,\,\,\,\,\,\,\,\,\,\sigma_{13} = T_{3}(\mathbf{e}_{1})} \\ {\sigma_{21} = T_{1}(\mathbf{e}_{2})\,\,\,\,\,\,\,\,\,\,\,\sigma_{22} = T_{2}(\mathbf{e}_{2})\,\,\,\,\,\,\,\,\,\,\,\,\sigma_{23} = T_{3}(\mathbf{e}_{2})} \\ {\sigma_{31} = T_{1}(\mathbf{e}_{3})\,\,\,\,\,\,\,\,\,\,\,\sigma_{32} = T_{2}(\mathbf{e}_{3})\,\,\,\,\,\,\,\,\,\,\,\,\sigma_{33} = T_{3}(\mathbf{e}_{3})} \end{array} \right.} \end{matrix}$$

{Then, the traction  $$

T_{i}(\mathbf{n})$$

acting on any plane with normal n follows as}

$$

\mathbf{T}(\mathbf{n}) = \mathbf{n} \cdot \mathbf{\sigma}\,\,\,\,\,\,\,\,\,\,\,\,\,\text{or     }T_{i}(\mathbf{n}) = n_{j}\sigma_{ji}$$

{ }

{To see this, recall the last result from the preceding section}

$$

T_{i}(\mathbf{n}) = T_{i}(\mathbf{e}_{1})n_{1} + T_{i}(\mathbf{e}_{2})n_{2} + T_{i}(\mathbf{e}_{3})n_{3}$$

{and substitute for $$

T_{i}(\mathbf{e}_{j})$$

in terms of the components of the Cauchy stress tensor}

$$

T_{i}(\mathbf{n}) = \sigma_{1i}n_{1} + \sigma_{2i}n_{2} + \sigma_{3i}n_{3} = n_{j}\sigma_{ji}$$

![](media/2.2-Internal forces_files/image025.gif){} \\

{ }

{The Cauchy stress tensor completely characterizes the internal forces acting in a deformed solid.

The physical significance of the components of the stress tensor is illustrated in the figure: $$

\sigma_{ji}$$

represents the ith component of traction acting on a plane with normal in the $$

\mathbf{e}_{j}$$

direction.}

{ }

{Note the Cauchy stress represents force per unit area of the deformed solid.

In elementary strength of materials courses it is called `true stress,' for this reason.}

{ }

{HEALTH WARNING: }{Some texts define stress as the transpose of the definition used here, so that }$$

\mathbf{T}(\mathbf{n}) = \mathbf{\sigma} \cdot \mathbf{n}\,\,\,\,\,\,\,\,\,\,\,\,\,\text{or     }T_{i}(\mathbf{n}) = \sigma_{ij}n_{j}$$

.{ }In this case the first index for each stress component denotes the direction of traction, while the second denotes the normal to the plane.{  }We will see later that Cauchy stress is always symmetric, so there is no confusion if you use the wrong definition.{  }But some stress measures are not symmetric (see below) and in this case you need to be careful to check which convention the author has chosen.{}

{ }

{ }

{ }

{2.2.4}{ Other stress measures $$

–$$

Kirchhoff, Nominal and Material stress tensors}

![](media/2.2-Internal forces_files/image027.gif){} \\

{ }

{Cauchy stress $$

\sigma_{ij}$$

(the actual force per unit area acting on an actual, deformed solid) is the most physical measure of internal force.

Other definitions of stress often appear in constitutive equations, however.  }

{ }

{The other stress measures regard forces as acting on the undeformed solid.

Consequently, to define them we must know not only what the deformed solid looks like, but also what it looked like before deformation.

The deformation is described by a displacement vector $$

\mathbf{u}(\mathbf{x})$$

and the associated deformation gradient}

$$

\mathbf{F} = \mathbf{I} + \mathbf{u} \otimes \nabla\,\,\,\,\,\,\,\,\,\,\,\, F_{ij} = \delta_{ij} + \frac{\partial u_{i}}{\partial x_{j}}$$

{as outlined in Section 2.1.

In addition, let $$

J = \det(\mathbf{F})$$

}

{ }

{We then define the following stress measures}

{ }

{![](media/2.2-Internal forces_files/image008.jpg) Kirchhoff stress $$

\mathbf{\tau = J\mathbf{\sigma}\,\,\,\,\,\tau_{ij} = J\sigma_{ij}$$

}}

{![](media/2.2-Internal forces_files/image008.jpg) }{Nominal (First Piola-Kirchhoff) stress }{ $$

\mathbf{S} = J\mathbf{F}^{- 1} \cdot \mathbf{\sigma}\,\,\,\,\,\,\,\, S_{ij} = JF_{ik}^{- 1}\sigma_{kj}$$

}{}

{![](media/2.2-Internal forces_files/image008.jpg) }{Material (Second Piola-Kirchhoff) stress }{ $$

\mathbf{\Sigma} = J\mathbf{F}^{- 1} \cdot \mathbf{\sigma} \cdot \mathbf{F}^{- T}\,\,\,\,\Sigma_{ij} = JF_{ik}^{- 1}\sigma_{kl}F_{jl}^{- 1}$$

}

{ }

{The inverse relations are also useful $$

–$$

the one for Kirchhoff stress is obvious $$

–$$

the others are}

$$

\mathbf{\sigma} = \frac{1}{J}\mathbf{F} \cdot \mathbf{S}\,\,\,\,\,\,\,\sigma_{ij} = \,\frac{1}{J}F_{ik}S_{kj}$$

$$

\mathbf{\sigma} = \frac{1}{J}\mathbf{F} \cdot \mathbf{\Sigma} \cdot \mathbf{F}^{T}\,\,\,\,\,\,\,\,\sigma_{ij} = \frac{1}{J}F_{ik}^{}\Sigma_{kl}F_{jl}^{}$$

{}

{ }

{The Kirchoff stress has no obvious physical significance.  }

{ }

{The nominal stress tensor can be regarded as the internal force per unit undeformed area acting within a solid, as follows}

{1.{      }}{Visualize an element of area dA in the deformed solid, with normal n, which is subjected to a force $$

d\mathbf{P}^{(n)}$$

by the internal traction in the solid;}

{2.{      }}{Suppose that the element of area dA has started out as an element of area $$

dA_{0}$$

with normal $$

\mathbf{n}_{0}$$

in the undeformed solid, as shown in the figure;}

{3.{      }}{Then, the force $$

d\mathbf{P}^{(n)}$$

is related to the nominal stress by $$

dP_{j}^{(\mathbf{n})} = dA_{0}n_{i}^{0}S_{ij}$$

}

{ }

{To see this, note that one can show (see Appendix D) that}

$$

dA\mathbf{n} = J\mathbf{F}^{- T} \cdot dA_{0}\mathbf{n}_{0}\,\,\,\,\,\,\,\,\,\,\,\,\, dAn_{i}^{} = JF_{ki}^{- 1}n_{k}^{0}dA_{0}$$

{}

{Recall that the Cauchy stress is defined so that}

$$

dP_{i}^{(\mathbf{n})} = dAn_{j}\sigma_{ji}$$

{}

{ }

{Substituting for $$

dAn_{j}$$

and rearranging shows that}

$$

dP_{i}^{(\mathbf{n})} = JdA_{0}n_{k}^{0}\left( {F_{kj}^{- 1}\sigma_{ji}} \right) = dA_{0}n_{k}^{0}S_{ki}$$

{}

{ }

this is the main reason that nominal and material stresses need to be defined.

The nominal stress is conjugate to the deformation gradient, while the material stress is conjugate to the Lagrange strain tensor.  }

{ }

{ }

{2.2.5 Stress measures for infinitesimal deformations}

{ }

{For a problem involving infinitesimal deformation (where shape changes are characterized by the infinitesimal strain tensor and rotation tensor) all the stress measures defined in the preceding section are approximately equal.}

$$

\sigma_{ij} \approx \tau_{ij} \approx S_{ij} \approx \Sigma_{ij}$$

{To see this, write the deformation gradient as $$

F_{ij} = \delta_{ij} + \partial u_{i}/\partial x_{j}$$

; recall that $$

J = \det(\mathbf{F) \approx 1 + \partial u_{k}/\partial x_{k}$$

}, and finally assume that for infinitesimal motions $$

\partial u_{i}/\partial x_{j} < < 1$$

.  Substituting into the formulas relating Cauchy stress, Nominal stress and Material stress, we see that}

$$

\sigma_{ij} = \frac{1}{J}F_{ik}S_{kj} \approx \frac{1}{1 + \partial u_{p}/\partial x_{p}}\left( {\delta_{ip} + \frac{\partial u_{i}}{\partial x_{p}}} \right)S_{pj} = S_{pj} + ... \approx S_{pj}$$

\paragraph{\texorpdfstring{{The same procedure will show that material stress and Cauchy stress are approximately equal, to within a term of order }$$

\partial u_{i}/\partial x_{j} < < 1$$

}{The same procedure will show that material stress and Cauchy stress are approximately equal, to within a term of order \textbackslash partial u\_\{i\}/\textbackslash partial x\_\{j\} \textless{} \textless{} 1}}

{ }

{ }

\paragraph{\texorpdfstring{2.2.6 Principal Stresses and directions }{2.2.6 Principal Stresses and directions }}

{ }

{For any stress measure, the principal stresses $$

\sigma_{i$$

and their directions $$

\mathbf{n}^{(i)}$$

}, with i=1..3 are defined such that}

$$

\mathbf{n}^{(i)} \cdot \mathbf{\sigma} = \sigma_{i}\mathbf{n}^{(i)}\,\,\,\,\,\,\,\text{or    }n_{j}^{(i)}\sigma_{jk} = \sigma_{i}n_{k}^{(i)}\,\,\,\,\,\,\,(\text{no sum on }i)$$

{Clearly, }

\begin{enumerate} \def\labelenumi{\arabic{enumi}.} \tightlist \item {The principal stresses are the (left) eigenvalues of the stress tensor} \item {The principal stress directions are the (left) eigenvectors of the stress tensor} \end{enumerate}

{ }

{The term `left' eigenvector and eigenvalue indicates that the vector multiplies the tensor on the left.

We will see later that Cauchy stress and material stress are both symmetric.

For a symmetric tensor the left and right eigenvalues and vectors are the same.}

![](media/2.2-Internal forces_files/image029.gif){} \\

{ }

\subsubsection{\texorpdfstring{Note that the eigenvectors of a symmetric tensor are orthogonal.

Consequently, the principal Cauchy or material stresses can be visualized as tractions acting normal to the faces of a cube.

The principal directions specify the orientation of this special cube.}{Note that the eigenvectors of a symmetric tensor are orthogonal.

Consequently, the principal Cauchy or material stresses can be visualized as tractions acting normal to the faces of a cube.

The principal directions specify the orientation of this special cube.}}

{ }

{One can also show that if }$$

\sigma_{1 > \sigma_{2} > \sigma_{3}$$

,} {then $$

\sigma_{1}$$

is the largest normal traction acting on any plane passing through the point of interest, while $$

\sigma_{3}$$

is the lowest.

This is helpful in defining damage criteria for brittle materials, which fail when the stress acting normal to a material plane reaches a critical magnitude.}

![](media/2.2-Internal forces_files/image031.gif){} \\

{ }

{In the same vein, the largest shear stress can be shown to act on the plane with unit normal vector $$

\mathbf{m}_{\text{shear}} = - (\mathbf{m}_{1} + \mathbf{m}_{3})/\sqrt{2}$$

(at 45\textsuperscript{o} to the $$

\mathbf{m}_{1}$$

and $$

\mathbf{m}_{3}$$

axes), and its magnitude is $$

\tau_{\text{max}} = \frac{1}{2}(\sigma_{1} - \sigma_{3})$$

.  This observation is useful for defining yield criteria for metal polycrystals, which begin to deform plastically when the shear stress acting on a material plane reaches a critical value.}

{ }

{ }

{ }

{2.2.7 Hydrostatic and Deviatoric Stress; von Mises effective stress}

{ }

{Given the Cauchy stress tensor $$

\text{σ$$

}, the following may be defined:}

{ }

{The Hydrostatic stress is defined as $$

\sigma_{h} = \text{trace(}\mathbf{\sigma})/3 \equiv \sigma_{kk}/3$$

}

{The Deviatoric stress tensor is defined as $$

{\sigma'}_{ij} = \sigma_{ij} - \sigma_{h}\delta_{ij}$$

}

{The Von-Mises effective stress is defined as $$

\sigma_{e} = \sqrt{\frac{3}{2}{\sigma'}_{ij}{\sigma'}_{ij}}$$

}

\paragraph{\texorpdfstring{ }{ }}

{The hydrostatic stress is a measure of the pressure exerted by a state of stress.

Pressure acts so as to change the volume of a material element.}

{ }

{The deviatoric stress is a measure of the shearing exerted by a state of stress.

Shear stress tends to distort a solid, without changing its volume. }

{ }

{The Von-Mises effective stress can be regarded as a uniaxial equivalent of a multi-axial stress state.

It is used in many failure or yield criteria.

Thus, if a material is known to fail in a uniaxial tensile test (with $$

\sigma_{11}$$

the only nonzero stress component) when $$

\sigma_{11} = \sigma_{crit}$$

, it will fail when $$

\sigma_{e} = \sigma_{crit}$$

under multi-axial loading (with several $$

\sigma_{ij} \neq 0$$

)}

{ }

\paragraph{\texorpdfstring{The hydrostatic stress and von Mises stress can also be expressed in terms of principal stresses as}{The hydrostatic stress and von Mises stress can also be expressed in terms of principal stresses as}}

$$

\begin{array}{l} {\sigma_{h} = \left( {\sigma_{1} + \sigma_{2} + \sigma_{3}} \right)/3} \\ {\sigma_{e} = \sqrt{\frac{1}{2}\left\{ {\left( {\sigma_{1} - \sigma_{2}} \right)^{2} + \left( {\sigma_{1} - \sigma_{3}} \right)^{2} + \left( {\sigma_{2} - \sigma_{3}} \right)^{2}} \right\}}} \end{array}$$

{ }

{The hydrostatic and von Mises stresses are invariants of the stress tensor $$

–$$

they have the same value regardless of the basis chosen to define the stress components.}

{ }

{ }

{2.2.8 Stresses near an external surface or edge $$

–$$

boundary conditions on stresses}{}

![](media/2.2-Internal forces_files/image033.gif){} \\

{ }

{Note that at an external surface at which tractions are prescribed, some components of stress are known.

Specifically, let n denote a unit vector normal to the surface, and let t denote the traction (force per unit area) acting on the surface.

Then the Cauchy stress at the surface must satisfy}

$$

n_{i}\sigma_{ij} = t_{j}$$

\subparagraph{\texorpdfstring{ }{ }}

{For example, suppose that a surface with normal in the $$

\mathbf{e}_{2}$$

direction is subjected to no loading.

Then (noting that $$

n_{i} = \delta_{i2}$$

) it follows that $$

\sigma_{2i} = 0$$

. In addition, two of the principal stress directions must be parallel to the surface; the third (with zero stress) must be perpendicular to the surface.}

{ }

{The stress state at an edge is even simpler.

Suppose that surfaces with normals in the $$

\mathbf{e}_{2}$$

and $$

\mathbf{e}_{1}$$

are traction free.

Then $$

\sigma_{1i} = \sigma_{2i} = 0$$

, so that 6 stress components are known to be zero.}

{ }

\title{A brief summary of vectors, matrices, and index notation}

\author{Mauricio Ponga$^*$} \address{Department of Mechanical Engineering, University of British Columbia, 2054 - 6250 Applied Science Lane, Vancouver, BC, V6T 1Z4, Canada} \cortext[mycorrespondingauthor]{Corresponding author} \ead{mponga@mech.ubc.ca}

\begin{abstract} These notes introduce the concept of index notation along with the definitions of some algebraic operations used in the course.

The notes are a compendium of several notes found online, books and self notes from the course. \end{abstract}

\begin{keyword} index notation, linear algebra, elasticity. \end{keyword}

\end{frontmatter}

\begin{equation} \alpha_1 = \bm a \cdot \bm m_1 = a_1 \bm e_1 \cdot \bm m_1 +  a_2 \bm e_2 \cdot \bm m_1 +  a_3 \bm e_3 \cdot \bm m_1, \end{equation} % \begin{equation} \alpha_2 = \bm a \cdot \bm m_2 = a_1 \bm e_1 \cdot \bm m_2 +  a_2 \bm e_2 \cdot \bm m_2 +  a_3 \bm e_3 \cdot \bm m_2, \end{equation} % \begin{equation} \alpha_3 = \bm a \cdot \bm m_3 = a_1 \bm e_1 \cdot \bm m_3 +  a_2 \bm e_2 \cdot \bm m_3 +  a_3 \bm e_3 \cdot \bm m_3. \end{equation}

This transformation is conveniently written as a matrix operation

\begin{equation} \bm \alpha = \bm Q \cdot \bm a =  [ \alpha] = [Q] [a] \end{equation} % where $\bm \alpha$ is a vector consisting in the components of $\bm a$ in the basis $\{ \bm m_1, \bm m_2, \bm m_3 \}$, and $\bm Q$ is a rotation matrix as follows

\begin{equation} \bm Q = \begin{pmatrix}   \bm m_1 \cdot \bm e_1 & \bm m_1 \cdot \bm e_2 & \bm m_1 \cdot \bm e_3  \\ \bm m_2 \cdot \bm e_1 & \bm m_2 \cdot \bm e_2 & \bm m_2 \cdot \bm e_3  \\ \bm m_3 \cdot \bm e_1 & \bm m_3 \cdot \bm e_2 & \bm m_3 \cdot \bm e_3  \\    \end{pmatrix}. \end{equation}

Notice that the products $\bm m_i \cdot \bm e_j$ have a physical interpretation, they represent the angles $\theta(\bm m_i, \bm e_j)$ between the basis $\bm m_i$ and $\bm e_j$. In index notation

\begin{equation} \alpha_i =  Q_{ij} a_j,      Q_{ij} = \bm e_i \cdot \bm m_j. \end{equation} % where the repeated index(es) indicate summation of these components.

For the above example, \begin{equation} \alpha_i =  Q_{ij} a_j = \sum_j^3 Q_{ij} a_j = Q_{i1} a_1+Q_{i2} a_2+Q_{i3} a_3 \end{equation}

One can also show that the rotation matrix is orthogonal satisfying the following relation \begin{equation} \bm Q^{-1} = \bm Q^T,      \bm Q  \bm Q^T = \bm Q^T  \bm Q = \bm I. \end{equation}

The proof is leave as an exercise to the students.

A hint is to work in two-dimensions and show that the rotation matrix can be written as

If $i = 1$, then $a_i$ is a scalar, also called a $\bm 0^{\text{th}$ order tensor}. A scalar can also be represented simply by $a$. If $i = 1, \ldots, k$, and $k > 1$ then $a_i$ is a vector, also called a $1^{\text{st}$ order tensor.}

Let us look at scalar-vector multiplication in index notation:

\begin{equation} \label{eq:scalar_vector_explicit} c \cdot {\bm a} = {\bm b} = \begin{pmatrix}   b_1 \\ b_2 \\ b_3    \end{pmatrix} = \begin{pmatrix}   c \cdot a_1 \\ c \cdot a_2 \\ c \cdot a_3    \end{pmatrix} \end{equation}

\begin{equation} \label{eq:scalar_vector_idx} c \cdot a_i  = b_i;      b_1 = c \cdot a_1;  b_2 = c \cdot a_2;  b_3 = c \cdot a_3; \end{equation}

It is simple to see that the index ($i$) is incremented between 1 and 3 in equation (\ref{eq:scalar_vector_idx}), and the multiplication is carried out, giving the same answer as in equation (\ref{eq:scalar_vector_explicit}).

\begin{tcolorbox}[colback=black!5!white,colframe=black!75!black,title=Important remark] The number of indices indicates the order of the tensor.  \\ The scalar ($c$) does not have an index, indicating that it is a 0$^{\text{th}}$ order tensor.  \\ The vector ($\bm a$) has one index ($i$), indicating that it is a 1$^{\text{st}}$ order tensor. \end{tcolorbox}

This is trivial for this case, but becomes useful later.

So in the case where two 1$^{\text{st}}$ order tensors are multiplied, the index $i$ cancels out, and this shows that the final result will not have an index, therefore it is a scalar result.

Again, these observations may be apparent here, but they are very useful for higher order tensors.

The repeated index is called a dummy index. \end{itemize} \end{tcolorbox}

Let $\bm a(t)$ be a vector whose magnitude and direction vary with time, $t$. Suppose that $\{ \bm i, \bm j, \bm k \}$ is a fixed basis, i.e., independent of time.

We may express $\bm a(t)$ in terms of components $(a_x, a_y, a_z)$ in the basis $\{ \bm i, \bm j, \bm k \}$ as

\begin{equation} \bm a(t) = a_x \bm i + a_y \bm j + a_z \bm k. \end{equation}

The time derivative of $\bm a$ is defined using the usual rules of calculus.

\begin{equation} \dot{\bm a}(t) = \frac{d}{dt}  \bm a(t) = \lim_{\epsilon \to 0} \frac{\bm a(t+\epsilon) -\bm a(t)}{\epsilon}, \end{equation} % or in components form as \begin{equation} \dot{\bm a}(t) =   {\dot a}_x {\bm i} + \dot{a}_y \bm j + \dot{a}_z \bm k. %{\dot a}_x \bm i % + \dot{a}_y \bm j + \dot{a}_z \bm k. \end{equation}

The definition of the time derivative of a vector may be used to show the following rules

Let $\bm v$ be a vector field in three dimensional space.

The divergence of $\bm v$ is a scalar field denoted by $\text{div} (\bm v)$ or $\nabla \cdot \bm v$. Formally, it is defined as $\tt trace(grad) \bm$ $\bm v$ (the trace is the sum of the diagonal terms or a matrix).

\begin{equation} \text{div} (\bm v) = \frac{\partial v_1}{\partial x_1} +  \frac{\partial v_2}{\partial x_2} + \frac{\partial v_3}{\partial x_3} \end{equation}

Alternatively, in index notation \begin{equation} \text{div} (\bm v) = \frac{\partial v_i}{\partial x_i}. \end{equation}

Let $\bm v$ be a vector field in three dimensional space.

The divergence of $\bm v$ is a scalar field denoted by $\text{curl} (\bm v)$ or $\nabla \times \bm v$. It is best defined in terms of its components in a given basis

\begin{equation} \nabla \times \bm v = \begin{pmatrix} \bm e_1 & \bm e_2 & \bm e_3 \\ \frac{\partial }{\partial x_1} &  \frac{\partial }{\partial x_2}  & \frac{\partial }{\partial x_3}  \\ v_1 &  v_2 & v_3   \end{pmatrix} = \bigg[ \frac{\partial v_3}{\partial x_2} -  \frac{\partial v_2}{\partial x_3}  \bigg] \bm e_1 + \ldots \end{equation}

Alternatively, in index notation \begin{equation} \big[ \nabla \times \bm v \big]_{i} \equiv \epsilon_{ijk} \frac{\partial v_j}{\partial x_k} \end{equation}

$i=1; j=1,\ldots,3;\longrightarrow$ Keep $i$ fixed and sum for all values of $j$ as it is incremented: \begin{equation} d_1 = A_{11} b_1 + A_{12} b_2 + A_{13} b_3 \end{equation} $i=2; j=1,\ldots,3;\longrightarrow$ Keep $i$ fixed and sum for all values of $j$ as it is incremented: \begin{equation} d_2 = A_{21} b_1 + A_{22 }b_2 + A_{23} b_3 \end{equation} $i=3; j=1,\ldots,3;\longrightarrow$ Keep $i$ fixed and sum for all values of $j$ as it is incremented: \begin{equation} d_3 = A_{31} b_1 + A_{32} b_2 + A_{33} b_3 \end{equation}

This is the same procedure as matrix-vector multiplication, except we are following the index notation rules, which say sum over repeated indices.

This procedure also illustrates another important technique: increment the repeated indices while keeping the unique indices fixed; when the repeated indices have been fully incremented, increment the unique index, reset the repeated index, and the increment the repeated index fully again.

Repeat this until all indices have been fully incremented at least once.

\begin{equation} \bm D = \bm A  \cdot \bm B \end{equation}

\begin{equation} D_{ik} = A_{ij} B_{jk}      i=1,2;   j = 1,\ldots,3; k=1,2 \end{equation}

Interpretation We must sum over the index $j$. The second dimension of $\bm A$ (a $2 \times 3$ 2$^{\text{nd}}$ order tensor) and the first dimension of $\bm B$ (a $3 \times 2$ 2$^{\text{nd}}$ order tensor) must match.

Finally, the resulting tensor $\bm D$, will be a $2 \times 2$ 2$^{\text{nd}}$ order, because the index $j$ cancels out and we are left with two unique indices ($i$ and $k$), each with a dimension of 2.

The indices $i$ and $k$ can be of arbitrary size.

Let us examine the mechanics of the multiplication in detail:

$i=1;  k=1; j=1,\ldots,3;\longrightarrow$ Keep $i$ and $k$ fixed and sum for all values of $j$ as it is incremented: \begin{equation} D_{11} = A_{11} B_{11} + A_{12} B_{21} + A_{13} B_{31} \end{equation}

$i=1;  k=2; j=1,\ldots,3;\longrightarrow$ Keep $i$ fixed, increment $k$ and sum for all values of $j$ as it is incremented: \begin{equation} D_{12} = A_{11} B_{12} + A_{12} B_{22} + A_{13} B_{32} \end{equation}

$i=2;  k=1; j=1,\ldots,3;\longrightarrow$ Keep $i$ and $k$ fixed, and sum for all values of $j$ as it is incremented: \begin{equation} D_{21} = A_{21} B_{11} + A_{22} B_{21} + A_{23} B_{31} \end{equation}

The Kronecker delta is a convenient way of expressing the identity in index notation:

\begin{equation} \delta_{ij} = \begin{cases} \delta_{ij}  = 1, & \mbox{if } i = j \\ \delta_{ij} = 0, & \mbox{otherwise } \end{cases} \end{equation}

The Kronecker delta follows all of the same rules of index notation.

\begin{equation} A_{ik} = \delta_{ij} A_{jk} \end{equation}

Where $i$ and $j$ have the same dimensions, therefore $A_{ik} = A_{jk}$. You should check, using index multiplication rules, that the Kronecker delta really does function as an identity.

Consider: why does $\delta_{ii} = 3$, not 1?

The permutation symbol is also known as the Levi-Civita operator.

It is defined as follows:

\begin{equation} \varepsilon_{ijk} = \begin{cases} +1, & \mbox{for a forward permutation of } ijk  \\ -1, & \mbox{ for a backward permutation of } ijk \\ 0, & \mbox{ if } i, j \mbox{or} k \mbox{are equal}. \end{cases} \end{equation}

Forward permutations are defined as three unique numbers which read $1,2,3$ from left to right (allowing for wrapping), e.g. $1,2,3$, $3,1,2$, or $2,3,1$. Backward permutations read $3,2,1$ from left to right (allowing for wrapping), e.g. $3,2,1$, $1,3,2$, or $2,1,3$. A useful relationship for the permutation operator is that:

\begin{equation} \varepsilon_{ijk} = -\varepsilon_{ikj} \end{equation}

This does not indicate, however, which one is positive or negative (or zero), just that they are of opposite sign.

This more complex operator is useful for defining cross products:

\begin{equation} \bm d =  \begin{pmatrix}  d_1 \\ d_2 \\ d_3 \end{pmatrix}  = \bm a \times \bm b  = \begin{pmatrix}  a_2b_3 - a_3b_2 \\ a_3 b_1 - a_1 b_3 \\ a_1 b_2 - a_2 b_1 \end{pmatrix} \end{equation}

\begin{equation} d_i = \varepsilon_{ijk} a_j b_k. \end{equation}

The two above definitions are identical, please check to verify this.

The use of index notation can be illustrated through the equations of linear elasticity.

First, we define the displacements as a 1st order tensor, with components in the principal Cartesian directions, considering only plane stress, therefore two dimensional.

\begin{equation} \mbox{dsplacements: } u_i,    i=1,2. \end{equation}

The well known linearized strains can be computed from the displacements:

\begin{equation} \epsilon_{ij} = \frac{1}{2} \big( u_{i,j}  +  u_{j,i}\big)    \mbox{with } j=1,2. \end{equation}

There are no repeated indices (the same indices on the opposite sides of the plus sign do not count), therefore there is no summation (except for the plus sign, of course).

Since there are two unique indices, the result is a 2$^{\text{nd}}$ order strain tensor.

Written in matrix form, the strain tensor as computed from equation (34) looks as follows:

\begin{equation} \epsilon_{ij} = \begin{pmatrix}  \frac{\partial u_1}{\partial x_1} & \frac{1}{2} \big( \frac{\partial u_1}{\partial x_2} + \frac{\partial u_2}{\partial x_1}   \big) \\  \frac{1}{2}  \big( \frac{\partial u_2}{\partial x_1} + \frac{\partial u_1}{\partial x_2}  \big) & \frac{\partial u_2}{\partial x_2}  \\ \end{pmatrix} \end{equation}

The constitutive relationship illustrates the power of the index notation, since the constitutive matrix is a 4$^{\text{th}}$ order tensor:

\begin{equation} \sigma_{ij} = C_{ijkl} \epsilon_{kl} \end{equation}

Since the multiplication of a 4$^{\text{th}}$ order tensor with a 2$^{\text{nd}}$ order tensor is extremely difficult to visualize, the index notation is critical.

There are two repeated indices on the righthand side ($k$ and $l$), therefore they will be summed over.

We already know that $k$ and $l$ go from $1, 2$, and we also know that the stress ($\sigma_{ij}$) tensor is of the same dimensions.

Therefore, all indices go from 1 . . . 2.

This means that the constitutive tensor is $2 \times 2 \times 2 \times 2$ and has 16 entries, for the simplified 2-d problem (81 entries in 3-d).

Let us multiply out equation , for greater detail.

\begin{equation} \sigma_{11} = C_{1111} \epsilon_{11} + C_{1112} \epsilon_{12} + C_{1121} \epsilon_{21} + C_{1122} \epsilon_{22} \end{equation}

\begin{equation} \sigma_{12} = C_{1211} \epsilon_{11} + C_{1212} \epsilon_{12} + C_{1221} \epsilon_{21} + C_{1222} \epsilon_{22} \end{equation}

\begin{equation} \sigma_{21} = C_{2111} \epsilon_{11} + C_{2112} \epsilon_{12} + C_{2121} \epsilon_{21} + C_{2122} \epsilon_{22} \end{equation}

\begin{equation} \sigma_{22} = C_{2211} \epsilon_{11} + C_{2212} \epsilon_{12} + C_{2221} \epsilon_{21} + C_{2222} \epsilon_{22} \end{equation}

Notice how, $i$ and $j$ are held fixed, while $k$ and $l$ are fully incremented and summed over.

A new equation is started when the values of $i$ or $j$ change.

For isotropic, linear elastic materials, Hooke's law gives us the following relationships between stress and strain for plane stress:

\begin{equation} \begin{cases} \sigma_{11} = \sigma_{xx} = \frac{E}{1-\nu^2} \big( \epsilon_{11} + \nu \epsilon_{22} \big) \\ \sigma_{12} = \sigma_{xy} = \frac{E}{1-\nu^2} (1-\nu) \epsilon_{12} = 2G \epsilon_12 = G\gamma_{12} \\ \sigma_{21} = \sigma_{yx} = \frac{E}{1-\nu^2} (1-\nu) \epsilon_{21} = 2G \epsilon_21 = G\gamma_{21} \\ \sigma_{22} = \sigma_{yy} = \frac{E}{1-\nu^2} \big( \epsilon_{22} + \nu \epsilon_{11} \big) \\ \end{cases} \end{equation}

